The '''American Osteopathic Board of Emergency Medicine''' ('''AOBEM''') is an organization that provides [[board certification]] to qualified [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine|Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine]] who specialize in the medical and surgical treatment of acutely ill patients with [[advanced cardiac life support]], [[Physical trauma|trauma]], and the management of other life-threatening medical issues ([[emergency physician|emergency physicians]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aobem.org/about_aobem.html |title=About AOBEM |author= |date= |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Emergency Medicine |accessdate=11 July 2012 }}</ref> The AOBEM is one of 18 [[Specialty (medicine)|medical specialty]] certifying boards of the [[American Osteopathic Association Bureau of Osteopathic Specialists]] approved by the [[American Osteopathic Association]] (AOA).<ref>{{cite web|title=AOA Specialty Certifying Boards|url=https://www.osteopathic.org/inside-aoa/development/aoa-board-certification/Pages/aoa-specialty-boards.aspx|publisher=American Osteopathic Association|accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hwic.org/experts/details.php?id=3114 |title=American Osteopathic Board of Emergency Medicine |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Health Workforce Information Center |accessdate=22 September 2012}}</ref> 

As of December 2011, 2,152 osteopathic emergency physicians held active certification with the AOBEM.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ayres|first=Ronald E|coauthors=S Scheinthal, C Gross, and E Bell.|title=Changes to Osteopathic Specialty Board Certification|journal=Journal of the American Osteopathic Association|year=2012|month=April|volume=112|issue=4|pages=226–231|url=http://www.jaoa.org/content/112/4/226.full.pdf+html|accessdate=26 August 2012}}</ref> 

==Board certification==
Board certification is potentially available to osteopathic emergency physicians who have successfully completed an AOA-approved [[medical residency|residency]] in emergency medicine, two years of practice, and successfully completed the required clinical, oral, and written examinations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aobem.org/part1requirements.html |title=AOBEM Part 1 Requirements |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Emergency Medicine |accessdate=14 September 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://aobem.org/part2requirements.html |title=AOBEM Part 2 Requirements |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Emergency Medicine |accessdate=14 September2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://aobem.org/part3requirements.html |title=AOBEM Part 3 Requirements |author= |year=2012 |work= |publisher=American Osteopathic Board of Emergency Medicine |accessdate=14 September2012 }}</ref> At one time, AOBEM offered certification eligibility via a practice track, allowing training in another specialty, practicing emergency medicine, and then passing the AOBEM certification exam.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}

